	<article>

		<header>
			
			<h1>LDC expansion of sugar production is on schedule</h1>

			
			<h4>
												29 March 2008
										</h4>

					</header>


		
		
					<p> Press reports indicate that Mozambican sugar production could more than double in four years from 240,000 tonnes to 500,000 tonnes. This reflects in part the success of Tongaat Hulett’s expansion plans in Mozambique, where milling capacity has grown from 1.1 million tonnes to 1.9 million tonnes. Meanwhile in Zambia Illovo announced the successful completion of its plans to expand sugar production from 200,000 tonnes to 400,000 tonnes per annum.</p><p> This contrasts to press reports suggesting a contraction of sugar production in Tongaat Hulett’s operations at the Triangle Estate (-`25%). However TH remains committed to expanding sugar production in Zimbabwe in the longer term, aiming for a ‘full capacity utilisation of 600,000 tonnes per annum, through increased supplies of cane from out-growers’. In this context a scheme to provide extension services to more than 650 small-scale sugar farmers has been launched, with smallholders providing 30% of the mill’s throughput.</p>
		
		
				<div class="box related">
			<h3>Sources</h3>
			
<p><b>Press reports: </b> </p><p><i>mamauhub</i>, March 4th 2008</p><p>

<a href="http://www.macauhub.com.mo/en/news.php?ID=4963" target="_self">http://www.macauhub.com.mo/en/news.php?ID=4963</a> <br /> </p><p><i>The Herald</i>, February 27th 2008</p><p>

<a href="http://allafrica.com/stories/printable/200802270100.html" target="_self">http://allafrica.com/stories/printable/200802270100.html</a> <br /> </p><p><i>Business Day</i>, February 26th 2008</p><p>

<a href="http://allafrica.com/stories/printable/200802260050.html" target="_self">http://allafrica.com/stories/printable/200802260050.html</a> <br /> </p><p><i>Zambia</i><i> Daily Mail</i> </p><p>

<a href="http://www.daily-mail.co.zm/media/news/viewnews.cgi?category=8&amp;id=1204188097" target="_self">http://www.daily-mail.co.zm/media/news/viewnews.cgi?category=8&amp;id=12...</a> <br /> </p><p><i>Zimbabwe</i><i> Standard</i>, March 2nd 2008</p><p>

<a href="http://allafrica.com/stories/printable/200803030533.html" target="_self">http://allafrica.com/stories/printable/200803030533.html</a> <br /> </p>		</div>
		
		
				<div class="box">
			<h3>Editorial comment</h3>
			<p> From October 1st 2009 ACP sugar exports will enjoy unlimited duty-free access to the EU market subject to a safeguard clause within a ceiling of 3.5 million tonnes. However this will coincide with a weakening of the price guarantees previously enjoyed, with the only price guarantees being that importers must not pay less than 90% of the reference price of €335 per tonne of raw sugar. However if the volume of ACP/LDC exports increases towards this ceiling a question arises as to what will be the market-price effects. This question is particularly relevant given the over-quota production in some parts of the EU. </p><p> In particular will it allow importers to lower prices paid to ACP suppliers to 90% of the import price, that is to say €301.5 per tonne? If ACP supplies continue to grow (as seems likely given the investment plans already announced in LDCs) what will be the impact on the market price for ACP raw sugars after October 2012 when prices paid by importers will be market related? This would be particularly relevant should a further round of sugar-sector price reductions be announced as part of the 2013 round of CAP reforms.</p>
		</div>
		
